We’ve eaten here twice now and were underwhelmed with the food both times. The main grievance being that the food lacked enough flavor and the ingredients felt cheap. The soup dumplings were too think and doughy for a place like this. The Shanghai Lo Mein was pretty flavorless and dry as it lacked enough sauciness. I almost wanted to splash my water on it, that’s how dry. The Shanghai Tofu tasted like it was packed with corn starch..super thick yet tasteless. We also got the spicy wontons but they came in a cup of jiffy tasting peanut butter and also lacked flavor aside from the dominating peanut. I’ve never had peanut butter wantons so am unsure if that’s a traditional dish or their own foul. It all left us feeling pretty bloated and sick both times too, I think from whatever thickening agent they use in their tasteless sauces. The restaurant itself/bar is very cute though, would be a great date spot if the foot was on the same level!

One doesn't necessarily associate "Williamsburg," home of hipster cafes and such, with "really good Chinese restaurant," but M. Shanghai is just that.  The scallion pancakes and "juicy buns" (i.e., soup dumplings) are fine appetizers; try the Shanghai-style (thick) lo mein, the diced fish, the salt-and-pepper shrimp, all good.  In fact, most of the menu is very good.  Having Keith Richards playing over the speakers is a reminder that, yes, this is Williamsburg...

The food was good.  But! Expensive compared to a traditional Chinatown restaurant.  No free green tea like a traditional restaurant.  The soup dumplings were too large, difficult to eat - but delicious.  $12.50 for a plate of steamed bok choy...  All that said, it's a good alternative to China Town if you say, live in Queens and don't want to take the trip into Manhattan.   I'd give 5 stars if they lower their prices a bit.

The food here is not authentic Chinese at all. It's worst than a Chinese take out. So disappointed. One of the noodles came out has no taste and we told the waiter that it has no taste at all, his didn't even offer to changed the dish but instead told us to add soy sauce ourselves. Their hot and sour soup tastes like sweet and sour soup, more on a sweet side. The awesome dish was the stir fried beef, the beef were over cooked and so hard. We also got  their fabulous which is shrimp with some noodles, cabbage and black fungus. That was not fabulous at all. The shrimp taste funny. Taste like old cooked shrimp and a little sour too. Overall I'm not coming to have another try here. Not worth the price at all. Don't waste your money here!

This is the worst food I've had in my life. Chicken in black bean sauce was some sort of shredded cat food in turkey grease, and the egg roll was more egg than roll. I am pretty sure they just threw some sugar and msg on a newspaper and rolled it inside of fried rat skin. Lastly, we tried the wonton soup which looked good but, again,  turkey grease is not a suitable broth and doesn't taste good. The wontons themselves may simply be boiled feces but I can't be sure. Do they wish to be some sort of poor-man's garbage? I don't know. But I do know I'd never go back here, not even if the zombies took over the neighborhood, leaving a red carpet on this beautiful place; I'd rather be eaten.

M Shanghai is Williamsburg's soup dumpling spot. Only one variety here: Steamed Juicy Pork Buns. I do miss having crab as well but I will be grateful that the soup dumpling they do make, they make wonderfully. Shanghai Style Lo Mein with shrimp, chicken & pork was also a good choice having thick noodles and mild but tasty sauce.Some dishes can be rather bland (e.g.  Shredded Pork with salted cabbage noodle soup).  My brunch time order for two from now on: 2 orders of Steamed Juicy Pork Buns, 1 Shanghai Style Lo Mein, and 1 Sautéed Spinach with fresh garlic.
